    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-10-28T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-10-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="242"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d242">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/11272: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hankow</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-10-28T13:00:00+08:00"
                            >October 28, 1930—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 28—8:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The following telegram has been sent to the Legation: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“October 28, 3 p.m. U. S. S. <hi rend="italic">Luzon</hi> silenced
                            fieldpiece on left bank of the river at mileage 166 above Hankow
                            yesterday. Many Red troops of [<hi rend="italic">all?</hi>] along river
                            bank. Naval authorities report Kienli practically deserted but river
                            quiet between that point and mileage 215.</p>
                        <p>Nanchow, Hunan, was captured by communist bandits October 22. Hwayung,
                            Hunan, also captured, communist bandits operating area numbering 4,000
                            to 1,000 [<hi rend="italic">5,000?</hi>]. Two Americans, Miss Hazel Todd
                            and W. W. Moore, who were reported as being there are in Hsucheng
                            (Anhwei) and Kuling, respectively.</p>
                        <p>Sixty-first Division arrived here yesterday and today and immediately
                            transferred to Wuchang.</p>
                        <p>Repeated to the Department.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
